WEBVTT

00:00.862 --> 00:10.000
♪♪

00:10.000 --> 00:19.137
♪♪

00:19.137 --> 00:20.517
Woman over radio:
The Coast Guard has received

00:20.517 --> 00:21.862
an EPIRB distress signal

00:21.862 --> 00:24.137
from the fishing vessel
Destination.

00:24.137 --> 00:29.172
Narrator: IT WAS A TRAGEDY THAT
IGNITED A SEARCH FOR ANSWERS.

00:29.172 --> 00:31.724
All vessels are requested
to keep a sharp lookout.

00:34.137 --> 00:37.310
Assist if possible and report
all studies to the Coast Guard.

00:37.310 --> 00:39.206
Break.

00:39.206 --> 00:42.827
SURROUNDED BY THE FLEET,
THE FISHING VESSEL DESTINATION

00:42.827 --> 00:46.344
DISAPPEARS WITHOUT SO MUCH
AS A MAYDAY CALL...

00:46.344 --> 00:49.344
Man over radio: WE'RE NOT
FINDING ANYTHING, LIKE, A RAFT.

00:49.344 --> 00:51.793
Man #2: We haven't been able
to find anyone...

00:51.793 --> 00:54.896
any signs of life.

00:54.896 --> 00:59.275
...TAKING CAPTAIN JEFF HATHAWAY
AND HIS ENTIRE 5-MAN CREW.

00:59.275 --> 01:03.586
♪♪

01:03.586 --> 01:06.827
Sean: SIX FISHERMEN
WILL NEVER MAKE IT HOME.

01:06.827 --> 01:08.793
THAT'S A HARD ONE TO DIGEST.

01:08.793 --> 01:11.517
I DON'T, UM,
I DON'T KNOW WHAT TO SAY.

01:11.517 --> 01:16.758
♪♪

01:16.758 --> 01:18.586
Casey over radio:
Sig, you on, man?

01:18.586 --> 01:21.413
[ RADIO BEEPS ]Sig: CASEY, WHAT'S UP, PAL?

01:27.137 --> 01:30.241
NO. I...

01:30.241 --> 01:32.344
ARE TALKING ABOUT
JEFF'S DESTINATION?

01:32.344 --> 01:34.206
MY...

01:34.206 --> 01:36.551
MY BUDDY? WHAT?

01:38.000 --> 01:44.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:54.655 --> 01:57.137
♪♪

01:57.137 --> 01:58.413
[ RADIO BEEPS ]

01:58.413 --> 02:03.655
♪♪

02:03.655 --> 02:04.965
Jake: I HAD WORKED ON
THE NORTHWESTERN

02:04.965 --> 02:06.310
FOR ABOUT 11 YEARS,

02:06.310 --> 02:08.620
AND JEFF AND SIG
WERE BEST FRIENDS.

02:08.620 --> 02:11.931
SO I'D ALWAYS GROWN UP WITH
THE CREW OF THE DESTINATION.

02:11.931 --> 02:13.793
THEY WERE KINDA LIKE
YOUR COUSINS, YOU KNOW?

02:13.793 --> 02:15.275
WHEN THEY PULLED UP,
IT WAS LIKE, OH, GREAT,

02:15.275 --> 02:16.517
THEY'RE COMING OVER.

02:16.517 --> 02:18.379
Bill: I EVEN KNEW THE CREW
AND THEIR DADS,

02:18.379 --> 02:20.793
AND THOSE GUYS WERE
THE MOST FUN IN THE HARBOR.

02:20.793 --> 02:23.448
MY NEPHEW WENT TO WORK
WITH JEFF.

02:23.448 --> 02:25.275
HE WASN'T ONBOARD THEN, BUT...

02:25.275 --> 02:28.241
WE'RE ALL INTIMATE.
WE'RE FAMILY.

02:28.241 --> 02:30.827
[ SWITCHES CLICK ]WE'RE ALL FRIENDS.

02:32.517 --> 02:35.655
Narrator: NOW, AFTER A 2-YEAR
INVESTIGATION...

02:35.655 --> 02:38.034
I HAVE NIGHTMARES ABOUT IT.

02:38.034 --> 02:40.827
I WON'T RELAX UNTIL I'M HOME.

02:40.827 --> 02:44.517
Narrator:
...THE MYSTERY MUST BE SOLVED.

02:44.517 --> 02:47.482
FISHING COMMUNITY AS A WHOLE
WAS HIT VERY, VERY HARD.

02:47.482 --> 02:49.448
WE HADN'T LOST A BOAT
IN SO MANY YEARS

02:49.448 --> 02:52.655
THAT PEOPLE THOUGHT CRAB FISHING
WAS SAFE FOR THE FIRST TIME,

02:52.655 --> 02:55.068
AND THEN YOU LOSE A BOAT
WITH ALL HANDS.

02:55.068 --> 02:56.931
IT WAS A SHOT ACROSS THE BOW,

02:56.931 --> 02:59.103
'CAUSE YOU REALLY DIDN'T EXPECT
THAT TO HAPPEN.

02:59.103 --> 03:03.344
THEY HAD A GREAT BOAT, A VERY
PROFESSIONAL, EXPERIENCED CREW.

03:03.344 --> 03:04.689
IT JUST DOESN'T MAKE SENSE.

03:04.689 --> 03:07.551
IT MAKES YOU THINK,
THIS COULD HAPPEN TO ME.

03:07.551 --> 03:08.965
WHAT HAPPENED SO FAST

03:08.965 --> 03:11.620
THAT THE GUYS COULDN'T
GET OFF A MAYDAY?

03:11.620 --> 03:13.034
I WANT TO KNOW WHAT HAPPENED
TO THAT BOAT

03:13.034 --> 03:15.206
BECAUSE I DON'T WANT IT
TO HAPPEN TO ME.

03:15.206 --> 03:18.172
--Captions by VITAC--
www.vitac.com

03:18.172 --> 03:21.172
CAPTIONS PAID FOR BY
DISCOVERY COMMUNICATIONS

03:21.172 --> 03:26.482
♪♪

03:26.482 --> 03:28.413
Narrator: THE FIRST CLUE TO
THE MYSTERY EMERGES

03:28.413 --> 03:32.241
IN THE EARLY MORNING HOURS --
NOT AS A MAYDAY...

03:32.241 --> 03:34.965
[ SIGNAL BEEPING ]

03:34.965 --> 03:38.793
Narrator: ...BUT AS AN AUTOMATED
DISTRESS BEACON.

03:38.793 --> 03:40.586
"EPIRB" STANDS FOR

03:40.586 --> 03:45.137
"EMERGENCY POSITION
INDICATING RADIO BEACON."

03:45.137 --> 03:47.586
IF THE EPIRB GETS SUBMERGED
IN WATER,

03:47.586 --> 03:50.793
IT SENDS OFF A SIGNAL
IN A FREQUENCY

03:50.793 --> 03:52.655
THAT THE COAST GUARD MONITORS,

03:52.655 --> 03:55.620
AND IT PROVIDES
YOUR EXACT LOCATION.

04:00.275 --> 04:02.275
Narrator:
FIVE HOURS INTO THE SEARCH,

04:02.275 --> 04:04.344
THE NEXT CLUE SURFACES.

04:08.586 --> 04:10.448
Man over radio:
FISHING VESSEL SILVER SPRAY,

04:10.448 --> 04:14.413
FISHING VESSEL SILVER SPRAY,
THIS IS COAST GUARD 6037.

04:14.413 --> 04:16.413
Narrator:
THE FIRST BOAT ON THE SCENE

04:16.413 --> 04:19.000
IS THE FISHING VESSEL
SILVER SPRAY.

04:24.000 --> 04:25.862
YEAH, ROGER.

04:25.862 --> 04:27.413
Prout: WE WERE
IN THE GENERAL VICINITY

04:27.413 --> 04:28.965
WHERE THE LAST KNOWN POSITION
WAS,

04:28.965 --> 04:30.344
AND THE COAST GUARD
DIRECTED US

04:30.344 --> 04:32.275
TO WHERE THE EPIRB
AND THE LIFE RING WERE.

04:38.275 --> 04:42.482
WE DROVE UP ON THAT RING,
AND IT WAS JUST SO EERIE...

04:45.103 --> 04:47.103
...HOW THE RING FLIPPED OVER

04:47.103 --> 04:48.551
AND SHOWED THE NAME
OF THE DESTINATION

04:48.551 --> 04:50.517
AS SOON AS WE DROVE UP TO IT.

04:50.517 --> 04:54.344
♪♪

04:54.344 --> 04:55.758
IT SHOWED US RIGHT THERE,

04:55.758 --> 04:57.793
"DESTINATION"
WRITTEN RIGHT ON IT.

05:00.241 --> 05:01.517
Man: OVER THERE.

05:01.517 --> 05:03.103
Narrator:
BUT THE NEXT DISCOVERY

05:03.103 --> 05:05.137
RAISES MORE QUESTIONS
THAN ANSWERS.

05:08.275 --> 05:11.344
Man: YO, IT'S RIGGED.
SOMEBODY TAPED IT.

05:11.344 --> 05:14.758
THIS IS HOW WE FOUND THE EPIRB
WHEN WE RETRIEVED IT.

05:14.758 --> 05:16.931
THAT EPIRB LINE
WAS TUCKED THROUGH

05:16.931 --> 05:19.103
THIS TAPED BRIDLE, SO...

05:19.103 --> 05:20.448
HOW DID THAT GET TAPED TOGETHER?

05:20.448 --> 05:24.275
THAT WAS DONE BY SOMEBODY
ONBOARD THE VESSEL,

05:24.275 --> 05:26.206
AFTER THE VESSEL HAD ITS MISHAP.

05:26.206 --> 05:28.551
WERE THESE PEOPLE INSIDE
THE WHEELHOUSE, TAPING IT?

05:28.551 --> 05:29.931
WERE THEY OUTSIDE ON THE DECK?

05:29.931 --> 05:31.275
WAS SOMEBODY TRYING TO HANG ON
TO THAT

05:31.275 --> 05:33.000
WITH THE COIL LINED TOGETHER?

05:33.000 --> 05:35.931
IS THIS...

05:35.931 --> 05:37.724
I TRIED PIECING THAT TOGETHER,
HOW IT HAPPENED,

05:37.724 --> 05:40.137
WHICH, A LOT OF OTHER PEOPLE
HAVE, TOO, AND...

05:40.137 --> 05:42.137
IT'S UNREAL HOW THAT HAPPENED.

05:42.137 --> 05:44.965
Narrator:
THIS, ALONG WITH SO MANY
OTHER UNANSWERED QUESTIONS

05:44.965 --> 05:47.620
SURROUNDING THE SINKING
OF THE DESTINATION,

05:47.620 --> 05:50.103
HAUNTS THE FLEET.

05:50.103 --> 05:54.689
I CAN ONLY IMAGINE THE CHAOS
AND THE FEAR THAT ENSUED

05:54.689 --> 05:57.000
ONBOARD THE DESTINATION
AS IT WAS SINKING.

05:59.413 --> 06:02.620
YOU COULD FIGURE THAT SHE ROLLED
OVER AND WENT STRAIGHT DOWN.

06:02.620 --> 06:03.931
CREW MEMBERS --
THEY WERE REALIZING

06:03.931 --> 06:06.137
THAT THERE'S WATER COMING IN,

06:06.137 --> 06:08.758
AND THEY WERE WONDERING,
"WHERE DO I GO?

06:08.758 --> 06:11.000
WHAT DO I DO? HOW DO I GET OUT?"

06:11.000 --> 06:12.172
AND THEN PROBABLY COMING
TO THE REALIZATION

06:12.172 --> 06:14.172
THAT THEY CAN'T GET OUT.

06:14.172 --> 06:15.310
IT'S A HORRIBLE THOUGHT.

06:15.310 --> 06:16.655
Narrator: TWO YEARS LATER,

06:16.655 --> 06:19.655
INVESTIGATIONS AIMED
TO IDENTIFY SPECIFIC FACTORS

06:19.655 --> 06:21.620
THAT COULD HAVE CAUSED
THE DESTINATION

06:21.620 --> 06:24.793
TO RAPIDLY LOSE STABILITY
AND CAPSIZE.

06:24.793 --> 06:26.379
Pruitt: SO ONE OF THE REASONS
FOR THE INVESTIGATION

06:26.379 --> 06:28.172
WAS TO DETERMINE,
IS THIS A ONE-OFF?

06:28.172 --> 06:31.068
IS THIS AN ANOMALY?
OR THIS AN ACTUAL TREND

06:31.068 --> 06:32.827
OF WHAT'S GOING ON WITHIN
THE FLEET?

06:32.827 --> 06:35.965
EVERYONE SEEMS TO BE KINDA
ON HEIGHTENED LOOKOUT

06:35.965 --> 06:38.482
FOR SAFETY ISSUES
AFTER THE DESTINATIONSINKING.

06:38.482 --> 06:42.068
A LOT OF CHANGES ARE BEING MADE
RIGHT NOW BY THE FISHERMEN.

06:42.068 --> 06:43.551
THEY'RE TAKING, ACTUALLY,
THE MEASUREMENTS

06:43.551 --> 06:45.758
AND THE CALCULATIONS
OF THEIR STABILITY.

06:45.758 --> 06:48.103
Narrator: OVER THE YEARS,
A SHIP'S WEIGHT CAN CHANGE

06:48.103 --> 06:51.275
WITH THE ADDITION
OF NEW MACHINERY AND GEAR.

06:51.275 --> 06:54.896
AND AS MORE WEIGHT IS PLACED
ABOVE THE WATERLINE,

06:54.896 --> 06:58.103
A BOAT BECOMES TOP HEAVY
AND UNSTABLE.

06:58.103 --> 07:00.344
A STABILITY TEST DETERMINES
JUST HOW MUCH WEIGHT

07:00.344 --> 07:03.724
A VESSEL CAN SAFELY CARRY
BEFORE CAPSIZING.

07:03.724 --> 07:06.793
♪♪

07:06.793 --> 07:08.931
AND WITH THE NORTHWESTERN
AND DESTINATION

07:08.931 --> 07:12.655
BEING NEARLY IDENTICAL
HOUSE-FORWARD BOATS...

07:12.655 --> 07:15.413
MR. CULVER,
ARE WE READY TO GO HERE TODAY?

07:15.413 --> 07:16.793
YES, WE ARE.

07:16.793 --> 07:19.827
Narrator: ...A HEAVY-HEARTED SIG
SCHEDULES A STABILITY TEST

07:19.827 --> 07:24.689
TO ENSURE THE SAFETY
OF HIS CREW AND VESSEL.

07:24.689 --> 07:26.827
WHAT HAPPENED TO THE DESTINATION
IS A REMINDER

07:26.827 --> 07:30.862
THAT WE GOT TO STAY IN TUNE
WITH TODAY,

07:30.862 --> 07:33.482
AND THE BEST WAY TO DO THAT
IS TO DO YOUR STABILITY REPORT

07:33.482 --> 07:37.172
SO THAT I CAN OPERATE
MY VESSEL SAFELY.

07:37.172 --> 07:38.965
I WANT TO DO IT
BECAUSE, NUMBER ONE,

07:38.965 --> 07:40.586
DESTINATIONSANK,
AND THAT'S --

07:40.586 --> 07:44.206
HE WAS ONE OF MY BEST FRIENDS,
SO THAT'S GOT ME SKITTISH.

07:44.206 --> 07:48.206
ALSO, WE PUT ON A NEW CRANE,
AND I WANT TO SEE

07:48.206 --> 07:50.862
HOW THAT'S AFFECTED
THE STABILITY OF THE BOAT.

07:50.862 --> 07:52.931
Narrator: THE TEST WILL USE
WEIGHTS AND MEASUREMENTS

07:52.931 --> 07:56.448
TO FACTOR THE NORTHWESTERN'S
BUOYANCY AND CENTER OF GRAVITY,

07:56.448 --> 07:58.862
TO DETERMINE IF ADDITIONS
OVER THE YEARS

07:58.862 --> 08:01.310
HAVE DANGEROUSLY
DESTABILIZED HER.

08:01.310 --> 08:02.482
THIS IS WAY OVER MY HEAD.

08:02.482 --> 08:03.793
I'LL LET YOU DO YOUR JOB,

08:03.793 --> 08:06.310
AND WE CAN GET THOSE WEIGHTS
AND GET STARTED?

08:06.310 --> 08:09.172
-YEAH.
-YES, SIR.

08:09.172 --> 08:12.206
Narrator: IN THE SEARCH TO SOLVE
THE MYSTERY OF THE DESTINATION,

08:12.206 --> 08:15.206
ONE PIECE OF THE PUZZLE
REMAINS ELUSIVE.

08:18.413 --> 08:20.689
THE BIG QUESTION
ON EVERYBODY'S MIND

08:20.689 --> 08:22.862
IS WHERE THERE WAS
NO MAYDAY CALL.

08:22.862 --> 08:24.931
AND WHEN TALK ABOUT A CREW
AND A CAPTAIN

08:24.931 --> 08:27.724
THAT'S SO EXPERIENCED,
WHAT HAPPENED?

08:27.724 --> 08:29.000
WHY DID IT GO SO QUICK?

08:29.000 --> 08:32.172
AND HOW COME NOBODY WAS ABLE
TO JUST REACH OUT

08:32.172 --> 08:33.965
AND GIVE OUT A MAYDAY?

08:33.965 --> 08:35.620
Man: WHAT HAPPENED
TO THE FISHING VESSEL

08:35.620 --> 08:37.793
AND ITS CREW OF SIX
OFF THE COAST OF ALASKA

08:37.793 --> 08:39.482
REMAINS A MYSTERY.

08:39.482 --> 08:41.551
Casey: THE FACT
THAT NOBODY HEARD A MAYDAY

08:41.551 --> 08:45.413
FROM THE DESTINATION,
IT BOTHERS ME A LITTLE BIT.

08:45.413 --> 08:47.862
YOU WOULD LIKE TO THINK THAT
SOMEBODY WOULD HAVE BEEN ABLE

08:47.862 --> 08:49.344
TO BE THERE TO HELP.

08:49.344 --> 08:51.137
I THINK THERE'S
A GOOD POSSIBILITY

08:51.137 --> 08:54.241
THAT SOMEBODY FELL ASLEEP
ON WATCH THROUGH ST. GEORGE

08:54.241 --> 08:56.965
AND TURNED THE WATCH ALARM OFF.

08:56.965 --> 08:59.586
WITH CRAB BOATS, YOU'VE GOT
WAVES, YOU'VE GOT WEATHER,

08:59.586 --> 09:02.448
YOU'VE GOT FIRES
THAT CAN BREAK OUT,

09:02.448 --> 09:04.344
FLOODING,
ANYTHING CAN HAPPEN,

09:04.344 --> 09:07.379
SO YOU HAVE TO HAVE SOMEBODY
WATCHING THE BOAT,

09:07.379 --> 09:08.965
WHICH WE CALL WHEEL WATCH.

09:08.965 --> 09:12.965
AND HE'S GOT TO KEEP US SAFE
WHILE WE'RE SLEEPING.

09:12.965 --> 09:15.965
Narrator: THE DESTINATIONSANK
JUST BEFORE SUNRISE,

09:15.965 --> 09:19.137
WHEN MOST CREWS
WOULD BE SLEEPING.

09:19.137 --> 09:20.724
Bill: SO HERE YOU ARE,
IN THIS WARM WHEELHOUSE,

09:20.724 --> 09:22.482
AND THE BOAT'S ROCKING
AND IT'S...

09:22.482 --> 09:25.379
YOU KNOW, WE'VE ALL DONE IT --
IT PUTS A GUY TO SLEEP.

09:26.931 --> 09:28.275
Narrator: COULD SOMEONE
HAVE FALLEN ASLEEP

09:28.275 --> 09:31.931
ON THE DESTINATION
DURING WHEEL WATCH?

09:31.931 --> 09:33.931
Jake: BASICALLY, YOU GOTTA
LOOK AT CRAB FISHING

09:33.931 --> 09:36.896
LIKE THE TRUCKING INDUSTRY,

09:36.896 --> 09:39.862
EXCEPT FOR OUR TRUCK
HAS TO GO 24/7.

09:39.862 --> 09:42.655
YOU CAN'T JUST PULL OVER
TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD

09:42.655 --> 09:44.896
AND TURN THE CAR OFF

09:44.896 --> 09:47.344
AND KNOW THAT
NOTHING'S GONNA HAPPEN.

09:47.344 --> 09:50.413
Narrator: THE 24/7 GRIND
PLAGUES ALL FISHERMEN.

09:50.413 --> 09:52.758
EVEN SEASONED SKIPPERS
FALL ASLEEP,

09:52.758 --> 09:55.000
SOMETIMES WHILE FISHING.

09:56.827 --> 10:00.034
IT'S A GRIND.
I'M STARTING TO GET DELIRIOUS.

10:00.034 --> 10:03.448
BUT THE POTS
KEEP COMING UP FULL!

10:03.448 --> 10:06.344
FULL! FULL! FULL!

10:06.344 --> 10:08.758
Narrator: AFTER 48 STRAIGHT
HOURS OF HAULING POTS,

10:08.758 --> 10:10.827
THE NORTHWESTERNCREW
AND CAPTAIN

10:10.827 --> 10:12.931
PUSH THROUGH
THE SEVERE EXHAUSTION.

10:12.931 --> 10:16.241
♪♪

10:16.241 --> 10:18.275
Sig: WE WANT TO GO IN WITH
A BOAT FULL,

10:18.275 --> 10:20.241
AND THE ONLY WAY TO DO THAT
IS TO PULL GEAR.

10:20.241 --> 10:22.482
AND THE ONLY WAY ICAN DO
THAT IS TO STAY AWAKE

10:22.482 --> 10:25.724
AND MAKE IT HAPPEN.

10:25.724 --> 10:29.655
-Man: MY GOD! [ LAUGHS ]
-[ MAN SHOUTS INDISTINCTLY ]

10:29.655 --> 10:33.068
[ YAWNS LOUDLY ]

10:33.068 --> 10:40.655
♪♪

10:40.655 --> 10:42.896
THERE'S NO POT COMING.

10:42.896 --> 10:44.482
WHAT'S GOING ON HERE?

10:44.482 --> 10:50.103
♪♪

10:50.103 --> 10:55.724
♪♪

10:58.965 --> 11:00.448
Sig: IT STILL HAPPENS,

11:00.448 --> 11:03.172
SO I HAVE TO JUST REMIND MYSELF
THAT THIS IS OUR OCCUPATION,

11:03.172 --> 11:04.586
THIS IS WHAT WE DO,

11:04.586 --> 11:07.241
AND YOU KNOW,
TRY TO PUSH THROUGH IT.

11:07.241 --> 11:09.206
Narrator:
COULD A FATIGUED CREWMAN

11:09.206 --> 11:11.896
HAVE BEEN ASLEEP AT THE HELM?

11:11.896 --> 11:15.689
EVEN IF THEY WERE,
SOMETHING MUCH WORSE THAN THAT

11:15.689 --> 11:17.517
IS WHAT BROUGHT THE BOAT DOWN.

11:19.172 --> 11:20.206
Narrator: COMING UP,

11:20.206 --> 11:22.620
THE SEARCH FOR ANSWERS
INTENSIFIES.

11:22.620 --> 11:25.655
IT CHANGED FISHING FOR EVERYBODY
THAT'S DRIVING A BOAT.

11:25.655 --> 11:27.275
Narrator: WHAT FORCES PUSHED
THE DESTINATION

11:27.275 --> 11:28.931
PAST HER LIMITS?

11:28.931 --> 11:31.931
JEFF HAD TO CATCH
191,000 POUNDS.

11:31.931 --> 11:34.379
[ LAUGHTER ]
-Narrator: WAS IT MAN?

11:34.379 --> 11:36.413
Sean: WE ALL PUT THAT PRESSURE
ON OURSELVES

11:36.413 --> 11:37.724
TO GO OUT THERE AND PERFORM.

11:37.724 --> 11:39.827
[ ALARM BLARING ]
-Man: FIRE IN THE ENGINE ROOM!

11:39.827 --> 11:41.206
Narrator: MACHINE...

11:41.206 --> 11:43.620
ICE WILL VERY EASILY
BUILD UP ON SHIPS.

11:43.620 --> 11:44.862
...MOTHER NATURE...

11:44.862 --> 11:46.758
Pruitt: AND NOW THEY ARE
INTO THE HEAT

11:46.758 --> 11:48.620
OF WHAT THE BERING SEA HAD
TO THROW AT THEM.

11:48.620 --> 11:49.862
...OR WORSE?

11:49.862 --> 11:51.586
MAYDAY, MAYDAY.

11:51.586 --> 11:53.758
IT DIDN'T HAPPEN.

11:53.758 --> 11:56.551
THIS COULD HAPPEN TO ME,
ANY DAY.

11:56.551 --> 11:59.344
♪♪

12:00.862 --> 12:04.965
♪♪

12:04.965 --> 12:06.862
Sig: YOU KNOW, WHEN I THINK
ABOUT THE DESTINATION,

12:06.862 --> 12:09.482
TO ME, IT WASN'T JUST
ANOTHER BOAT.

12:09.482 --> 12:12.034
NO, THESE GUYS WERE OUR FRIENDS.
WE KNEW ALL OF THEM.

12:12.034 --> 12:13.724
IT MAKES YOU THINK --
IF IT COULD HAPPEN TO THEM,

12:13.724 --> 12:15.551
CAN IT HAPPEN TO ME?

12:15.551 --> 12:16.896
Narrator:
THE CAPSIZED SINKING

12:16.896 --> 12:18.586
OF THE FISHING VESSEL
DESTINATION

12:18.586 --> 12:21.275
HAS HAUNTED THE FLEET
FOR TWO YEARS.

12:21.275 --> 12:23.448
Sig: I'VE GOT FAMILY ONBOARD.
I HAVE A SON-IN-LAW.

12:23.448 --> 12:26.655
HELL, I'VE GOT A DAUGHTER THAT'S
WORKING ON THE NORTHWESTERN.

12:26.655 --> 12:30.896
AND I WANT TO MAKE SURE MY BOAT
IS SAFE AS IT CAN BE.

12:30.896 --> 12:32.482
Narrator:
AND WITH NO SURVIVORS,

12:32.482 --> 12:34.517
THE FLEET IS DETERMINED
TO UNDERSTAND

12:34.517 --> 12:36.275
HOW ONE OF
THE BEST-MAINTAINED BOATS

12:36.275 --> 12:39.379
IN THE INDUSTRY
COULD HAVE BECOME UNSTABLE.

12:39.379 --> 12:42.068
Sig: NOW THAT WE'RE IN SEATTLE
DOING SHIPYARD WORK,

12:42.068 --> 12:45.137
MIGHT AS WELL GET
A NEW STABILITY REPORT.

12:45.137 --> 12:47.172
Narrator: DOCKED AT
THE PACIFIC FISHERMEN SHIPYARD

12:47.172 --> 12:49.689
IN SEATTLE,
SIG CHECKS ON THE PROGRESS

12:49.689 --> 12:52.448
OF THE NORTHWESTERN'S
STABILITY TEST.

12:52.448 --> 12:54.827
WHEN COMPLETE, THE RESULTS
WILL TELL HIM

12:54.827 --> 12:58.068
IF HIS BOAT IS STILL SEAWORTHY.

12:58.068 --> 13:00.655
Sig: SHE'LL GO DOWN IN
THE WATERLINE WHEN WE'RE HEAVY.

13:00.655 --> 13:03.103
AND THEN OTHER THAN THAT, THERE
HASN'T BEEN ANY MAJOR CHANGES,

13:03.103 --> 13:04.310
OTHER THAN THAT CRANE.

13:04.310 --> 13:05.482
YEAH.

13:05.482 --> 13:08.034
MOVE IT UP.

13:08.034 --> 13:10.517
Narrator: BUT ONE QUESTION ABOUT
THE TRAGIC SINKING

13:10.517 --> 13:13.620
IS PARTICULARLY VEXING.

13:13.620 --> 13:15.172
IF YOU'RE IN THE WHEELHOUSE

13:15.172 --> 13:17.931
AND SOMETHING SUDDEN
OR DRASTIC HAPPENS,

13:17.931 --> 13:21.206
USUALLY YOU GOT TIME TO JUST,
"MAYDAY, MAYDAY."

13:21.206 --> 13:22.724
IT DIDN'T HAPPEN.

13:22.724 --> 13:27.551
AND SO FOR THAT REASON, IT'S
BROUGHT ON A LOT OF SPECULATION.

13:27.551 --> 13:29.103
WAS THERE SOMEBODY
IN THE WHEELHOUSE

13:29.103 --> 13:30.275
ON THE DESTINATION?

13:30.275 --> 13:31.620
WE DON'T KNOW THAT, YOU KNOW.

13:31.620 --> 13:33.275
SOMEBODY MIGHT HAVE BEEN DOWN
IN THAT ENGINE ROOM.

13:33.275 --> 13:34.965
THEY MAY HAVE HAD A PROBLEM
DOWN THERE.

13:34.965 --> 13:36.448
ONE THING I CAN TELL YOU
ABOUT JEFF

13:36.448 --> 13:38.689
IS THAT
HE WOULD MAKE YOU GO DOWN --

13:38.689 --> 13:40.275
AND I KNOW THIS FOR FACT...

13:40.275 --> 13:42.206
YOU KNOW, YOU TAKE A WATCH,

13:42.206 --> 13:43.655
AND THEN YOU GO DOWN
TO THE ENGINE ROOM.

13:43.655 --> 13:47.517
YOU'RE ALWAYS GOING UP AND DOWN
TO CHECK THAT ENGINE ROOM.

13:47.517 --> 13:49.862
Narrator: COULD THE CREWMAN
ON DESTINATION'SWATCH

13:49.862 --> 13:52.517
SIMPLY HAVE BEEN CONDUCTING
HIS ROUTINE ROUNDS

13:52.517 --> 13:54.551
WHEN SOMETHING WENT WRONG?

13:54.551 --> 13:56.241
Sig: MY BROTHER NORMAN,
YOU KNOW,

13:56.241 --> 13:57.586
HE WAS DOWN IN THE ENGINE ROOM.

13:57.586 --> 14:01.689
NEXT THING YOU KNOW,
HE FELL, HAD A SEIZURE.

14:01.689 --> 14:05.034
IT HAPPENS. AND THAT WAS AT
THE DOCK, THANK GOD.

14:05.034 --> 14:08.068
♪♪

14:08.068 --> 14:12.103
HE TOOK A STEP HERE,
ROLLED OFF, AND HIT THAT.

14:18.862 --> 14:21.482
♪♪

14:21.482 --> 14:23.379
WHEN I THINK
ABOUT MY BROTHER NORMAN,

14:23.379 --> 14:26.827
YOU KNOW, HAD HE BEEN ON WATCH,
HAD WE HAD BEEN AT SEA,

14:26.827 --> 14:30.379
HE COULD HAVE BEEN LAYING THERE
FOR DEAD FOR HOURS ON END

14:30.379 --> 14:34.206
BEFORE ANYBODY WOKE UP
AND ACTUALLY NOTICED

14:34.206 --> 14:36.206
THAT THERE WAS NOBODY
IN THE WHEELHOUSE.

14:39.241 --> 14:40.896
THERE'S SO MANY
DIFFERENT REASONS THAT

14:40.896 --> 14:44.241
MAYBE NOBODY'S IN THE WHEELHOUSE
TO DO THAT MAYDAY.

14:44.241 --> 14:48.172
MAYBE THE BOAT JUST TOOK
A TURN FOR THE WORSE.

14:48.172 --> 14:50.551
Narrator: TO STAY ON SCHEDULE,
THE DESTINATIONSHOULD HAVE BEEN

14:50.551 --> 14:53.896
STEAMING AT A CONSTANT RATE
TO SAINT PAUL,

14:53.896 --> 14:56.413
BUT AIS SATELLITE
TRACKING DATA

14:56.413 --> 14:59.275
SHOWS THAT DURING
THE BOAT'S FINAL HOURS,

14:59.275 --> 15:01.689
IT DRAMATICALLY
CHANGED SPEEDS --

15:01.689 --> 15:05.103
A POSSIBLE INDICATION
OF A MECHANICAL PROBLEM.

15:05.103 --> 15:07.862
[ ALARM BLARING ]

15:07.862 --> 15:09.344
Man #1: WHAT'S GOING ON?

15:09.344 --> 15:11.034
Man #2:
FIRE IN THE ENGINE ROOM!

15:11.034 --> 15:12.586
Narrator: ABOARD THE SAGA...

15:12.586 --> 15:16.344
[ COUGHING ]

15:16.344 --> 15:19.172
MY MAIN ENGINES ARE OFF!

15:19.172 --> 15:22.172
[ CONTINUES COUGHING ]

15:22.172 --> 15:24.896
I CAN'T EVEN TURN THE BOAT!

15:24.896 --> 15:26.758
[ COUGHS ]

15:26.758 --> 15:29.344
[ ALARM CONTINUES BLARING ]

15:29.344 --> 15:31.413
[ VOMITS ]

15:31.413 --> 15:33.724
HAVING A FIRE IS
THE MOST DANGEROUS THING

15:33.724 --> 15:35.172
THAT CAN HAPPEN ON A BOAT.

15:35.172 --> 15:37.068
ALL'S IT TAKES IS
A LITTLE EXHAUST LEAK,

15:37.068 --> 15:39.379
JUST A TINY LITTLE PINHOLE,

15:39.379 --> 15:43.344
AND YOU CAN
KILL THE ENTIRE CREW.

15:43.344 --> 15:45.172
EVERYBODY, GET OUT OF
THE ENGINE ROOM.

15:45.172 --> 15:46.862
YOU DO NOT WANT TO
BREATHE THAT.

15:46.862 --> 15:50.448
[ COUGHING ]

15:50.448 --> 15:53.068
STARBOARD SIDE CLUTCH?

15:53.068 --> 15:54.310
YEAH. YEAH.

15:54.310 --> 15:55.862
I THINK IT'S THE CLUTCH
BURNED OUT.

15:55.862 --> 15:58.827
AND SMOKE JUST STARTS
POURING UP.

16:00.896 --> 16:03.586
Jake: IT WOULD HAVE EVENTUALLY
GOT TO THE HYDRAULIC OIL,

16:03.586 --> 16:08.103
ERUPTED IN AN EXPLOSION,
AND WE WOULD HAVE ALL BEEN DEAD.

16:08.103 --> 16:11.413
SO THANK GOD THAT THE GUYS
CAUGHT IT.

16:11.413 --> 16:13.862
Narrator: WHAT STARTED AS
A BURNED-OUT DRIVE CLUTCH,

16:13.862 --> 16:17.034
RESULTED IN
A SHIP-WIDE EMERGENCY,

16:17.034 --> 16:19.068
AND...

16:19.068 --> 16:21.275
AN EMPTY WHEELHOUSE.

16:21.275 --> 16:23.517
WHEN THERE'S A PROBLEM
IN THE ENGINE ROOM,

16:23.517 --> 16:26.103
I DON'T WANT TO WAIT
FOR SOMEBODY ELSE,

16:26.103 --> 16:30.034
I DON'T WANT THEM TO MAKE
ANY MISTAKES, SO I GO DOWN.

16:35.862 --> 16:39.310
I'VE PUT MY BOAT IN THAT
POSITION A LOT OF THE TIMES.

16:39.310 --> 16:43.068
IT SAVED US, BECAUSE I WAS
THE ONE IN THE ENGINE ROOM

16:43.068 --> 16:45.655
FIXING EVERYTHING,

16:45.655 --> 16:48.620
BUT ULTIMATELY, IT COULD HAVE
KILLED US AT THE SAME TIME.

16:48.620 --> 16:51.275
Narrator: DID A FIRE OR SOME
OTHER MECHANICAL EMERGENCY

16:51.275 --> 16:54.379
LEAD TO AN EMPTY WHEELHOUSE
ON THE DESTINATION?

16:54.379 --> 16:55.896
WE'RE NEVER GONNA KNOW.

16:55.896 --> 16:59.310
I THINK WHOEVER WAS ON THE WHEEL
WAS NOT IN THE WHEELHOUSE.

16:59.310 --> 17:01.137
MAYBE SOMEBODY FORGOT
THEIR READING GLASSES

17:01.137 --> 17:03.931
AND WENT DOWNSTAIRS,
AND THAT'S WHEN IT HAPPENED.

17:03.931 --> 17:05.586
Narrator:
EMPTY WHEELHOUSE OR NOT,

17:05.586 --> 17:07.964
WHEN DISASTER BEFALLS
A FISHING BOAT,

17:07.964 --> 17:09.517
MOST CRABBERS AGREE --

17:09.517 --> 17:12.964
THERE'S ONE FACTOR THAT CAN
NEVER BEEN FULLY RULED OUT,

17:12.964 --> 17:16.550
ONE THAT DRIVES MEN
AND MACHINES TO THEIR LIMITS...

17:16.550 --> 17:18.550
[ LAUGHTER ]
-Man: WHOA!

17:18.550 --> 17:20.448
Narrator:
...THE PRESSURE TO PRODUCE.

17:20.448 --> 17:22.172
THE CRABBER MENTALITY IS,

17:22.172 --> 17:25.619
WORK HARDER THAN EVERYBODY ELSE,
AND YOU'LL SUCCEED.

17:25.619 --> 17:28.896
-LOOK AT THIS!
-MONEY! MONEY! MONEY!

17:28.896 --> 17:34.482
JEFF HAD 12 TO 13 DAYS
TO CATCH 191,000 POUNDS.

17:34.482 --> 17:37.724
AND AN OPILIO WEIGHS ONE POUND.

17:37.724 --> 17:41.172
HE NEEDED TO CATCH
191,000 OF THEM.

17:41.172 --> 17:42.379
Man: WHOO!

17:42.379 --> 17:45.413
THE PRESSURE IS AMAZING
BECAUSE IF YOU MISS,

17:45.413 --> 17:47.758
YOU HAVE THE BIGGEST PORTION
OF YOUR INCOME FOR THE YEAR

17:47.758 --> 17:49.482
THAT MIGHT NOT BE THERE.

17:49.482 --> 17:51.655
I NEED TO GET THIS BOAT
PAID FOR.

17:51.655 --> 17:52.758
WHOA. LOOK OUT.

17:52.758 --> 17:55.379
Man: HEY, HEADS UP!
HEADS UP!

17:55.379 --> 17:57.931
WHOA!

17:57.931 --> 18:00.172
IF WE SPEND THIS WHOLE SEASON
WAITING FOR WEATHER,

18:00.172 --> 18:03.517
WE WOULD NEVER GET
ANYTHING DONE.

18:03.517 --> 18:05.758
Sean: WE ALL PUT THAT PRESSURE
ON OURSELVES

18:05.758 --> 18:06.862
TO GO OUT THERE AND PERFORM.

18:06.862 --> 18:08.034
WE WANT TO BE BETTER
THAN THE NEXT GUY.

18:08.034 --> 18:11.034
I'M NOT STOPPING
UNTIL THIS BOAT'S FULL.

18:11.034 --> 18:12.586
IF WE SOMEHOW DON'T HIT
OUR NUMBER,

18:12.586 --> 18:14.724
THEN I DON'T DESERVE
TO BE A CAPTAIN.

18:14.724 --> 18:16.586
Bill: WE DON'T REALLY
HAVE A CHOICE ABOUT HAULING.

18:16.586 --> 18:19.379
♪♪

18:19.379 --> 18:21.620
HOW YOU GONNA REDUCE
ANY OF THE STRESS?

18:21.620 --> 18:25.344
MAYBE SOFT MUSIC AND MAYBE
SOME OILS IN THE AIR?

18:25.344 --> 18:27.793
I DON'T KNOW. HOW ELSE
YOU GONNA REDUCE STRESS?

18:27.793 --> 18:30.241
♪♪

18:30.241 --> 18:31.413
Narrator: COMING UP...

18:31.413 --> 18:34.724
ICE WILL VERY EASILY
BUILD UP ON SHIPS.

18:34.724 --> 18:36.586
OVER 100,000 POUNDS...

18:36.586 --> 18:39.172
♪♪

18:39.172 --> 18:40.758
...AND THEN IT STARTS TILTING.

18:40.758 --> 18:43.724
Man: RIGHT NOW, WE'RE FIGHTING
FOR SURVIVAL.

18:45.068 --> 18:46.241
SHE GOES OVER.

18:46.241 --> 18:49.379
♪♪

18:51.793 --> 18:54.448
Narrator:
WITH THE NORTHWESTERN'S
STABILITY TEST IN PROGRESS,

18:54.448 --> 18:57.620
WEIGHTS ARE USED TO CALCULATE
THE SHIP'S INCLINE

18:57.620 --> 19:00.448
AND DETERMINE HOW MANY TONS
CAN BE CARRIED

19:00.448 --> 19:04.517
IN SEVERE CONDITIONS
BEFORE CAPSIZING.

19:04.517 --> 19:08.724
THIS COULD BE A VERY POSITIVE
THING OR A NEGATIVE THING.

19:08.724 --> 19:10.413
YOU KNOW, EVERY TIME
WE DO A STABILITY TEST,

19:10.413 --> 19:12.931
AS A FISHERMAN, YOU WANT TO GET
THE MOST POTS YOU CAN

19:12.931 --> 19:14.379
SO THAT YOU KNOW THAT
YOU'RE SAFE

19:14.379 --> 19:16.827
BUT YOU KNOW HOW MUCH
YOU CAN PUT ON.

19:16.827 --> 19:20.551
ALSO, FOR ME, I WANT TO KNOW
HOW MANY POTS I CAN PUT ON

19:20.551 --> 19:24.206
WITH ONE TANK OF WATER,
TWO, AND THREE,

19:24.206 --> 19:26.793
SO THAT I CAN OPERATE
MY VESSEL SAFELY.

19:28.379 --> 19:30.448
DEPENDING ON HOW MANY POTS
YOU HAVE ONBOARD

19:30.448 --> 19:33.034
AND WHAT
YOUR STABILITY PORT READS,

19:33.034 --> 19:36.310
YOUR CRAB TANKS EITHER
HAVE TO BE COMPLETELY FULL

19:36.310 --> 19:38.379
OR COMPLETELY EMPTY.

19:38.379 --> 19:39.724
AND THAT'S JUST THE BOTTOM LINE.

19:39.724 --> 19:41.034
WHEN THEY'RE FULL, YOU'RE SAFE.

19:41.034 --> 19:42.586
WHEN THEY'RE EMPTY,
YOU'RE SAFE.

19:42.586 --> 19:45.344
HALF-FULL OF WATER? SLACK TANK.

19:45.344 --> 19:47.793
Narrator: WHEN WATER
IN A HALF-FULL CRAB TANK,

19:47.793 --> 19:51.275
OR, SLACK TANK,
SHIFTS BACK AND FORTH,

19:51.275 --> 19:53.172
IT CAN CAUSE AN IMBALANCE

19:53.172 --> 19:58.965
AND TIP THE VESSEL TOO FAR TO
ONE SIDE, CAPSIZING IT.

19:58.965 --> 20:02.482
Man: WATER DOWN.

20:02.482 --> 20:03.689
Sig: YOU KNOW,
WE HAD A SLACK TANK

20:03.689 --> 20:05.172
NOT TOO LONG AGO
ON THE NORTHWESTERN,

20:05.172 --> 20:08.275
AND STRANGELY ENOUGH,
I MEAN, YOU CAN FEEL IT.

20:08.275 --> 20:11.448
♪♪

20:15.448 --> 20:18.620
OH, THAT'S A BIG-ASS TURN.

20:18.620 --> 20:21.655
NOW I DIDN'T FEEL THE WATER
SURGING AS MUCH,

20:21.655 --> 20:23.448
'CAUSE I WAS GOING UP
AGAINST IT,

20:23.448 --> 20:26.896
BUT I DID FEEL THE BOAT
WAS GETTING HEAVIER AND HEAVIER.

20:26.896 --> 20:28.758
AND ALL OF A SUDDEN, I'M LIKE,
"WAIT A MINUTE..."

20:28.758 --> 20:30.965
Sig:
SOMETHING'S WRONG.

20:34.551 --> 20:36.103
OKAY?
-YEAH.

20:37.413 --> 20:41.758
♪♪

20:43.068 --> 20:47.344
♪♪

20:47.344 --> 20:50.000
THAT'S COME UP.

20:50.000 --> 20:53.137
THAT TANK IS HALF-FULL.

20:53.137 --> 20:55.724
IT'S SLOWLY FILLING UP.

20:55.724 --> 20:57.379
YOU KNOW, IT'S VERY SERIOUS.

20:57.379 --> 20:59.413
WE HAVE
ALL THESE SAFETY MEASURES.

20:59.413 --> 21:02.793
WE'VE GOT A HIGH WATER ALARM,
A LOW WATER ALARM.

21:02.793 --> 21:05.586
THERE'S AN OPENING HERE
AND IT'S COMING IN

21:05.586 --> 21:07.172
AND IT'S FILLING.

21:07.172 --> 21:09.068
THE ALARMS FAILED.

21:11.724 --> 21:13.689
COME ON, BABY.

21:13.689 --> 21:17.206
♪♪

21:17.206 --> 21:18.344
[ BEEPING ]

21:18.344 --> 21:19.724
YEAH!

21:19.724 --> 21:22.068
AND WE HAVE A PUMP.

21:22.068 --> 21:25.206
AND I'M TELLING YOU, THAT WAS
A REAL, REAL SCARY MOMENT

21:25.206 --> 21:28.241
BECAUSE I KNOW WHAT CAN HAPPEN.

21:28.241 --> 21:30.413
Narrator: WAS A SLACK TANK
THE DEADLY CULPRIT

21:30.413 --> 21:33.000
IN THE SINKING
OF THE DESTINATION?

21:33.000 --> 21:38.000
OR WAS IT JUST THE STRAW
THAT BROKE THE CAMEL'S BACK?

21:38.000 --> 21:41.103
Sig: IT'S ALL ABOUT TRYING
TO KEEP THE WATER OFF THE DECK.

21:41.103 --> 21:43.724
WE HAVE SCUPPERS ON BOARD.

21:43.724 --> 21:46.896
WATER GETS ON DECK.
IT'S GOT TO GO SOMEWHERE.

21:46.896 --> 21:48.793
IT GOES OUT THESE SCUPPERS.

21:48.793 --> 21:52.000
♪♪

21:52.000 --> 21:53.724
ONE OF THE CONCERNS ON ANY BOAT

21:53.724 --> 21:56.689
IS WHEN YOU'RE ICING UP,
THOSE CAN FREEZE UP.

21:56.689 --> 22:00.482
WHEN THEY FREEZE UP, ALL THAT
WATER THAT'S ACCUMULATED

22:00.482 --> 22:01.931
HAS NO PLACE TO GO.

22:01.931 --> 22:06.172
YOU'VE GOT THOUSANDS AND
THOUSANDS OF POUNDS OF WATER,

22:06.172 --> 22:07.862
WANTS TO GO SOMEWHERE.

22:07.862 --> 22:10.172
AND THAT WILL KEEL
AND LIST THE BOAT OVER

22:10.172 --> 22:12.655
IF IT'S GOT NO PLACE TO GO.

22:12.655 --> 22:14.517
SO THE SCUPPERS ARE
VERY IMPORTANT

22:14.517 --> 22:18.034
WHEN YOU'RE TALKING ABOUT
ICING CONDITIONS.

22:18.034 --> 22:20.655
Casey: I WAS 80 MILES NORTHWEST
OF THE DESTINATION,

22:20.655 --> 22:22.689
AND THAT NIGHT, IN 45 MINUTES,

22:22.689 --> 22:26.103
I COMPLETELY CLOSED THE BOW
OF THE CORNELIAWITH ICE.

22:26.103 --> 22:29.758
THAT'S THE FASTEST
I'VE EVER BUILT ICE IN MY LIFE.

22:29.758 --> 22:31.448
Narrator:
BUT IF THERE'S ONE THREAT

22:31.448 --> 22:33.275
THAT'S WORSE
THAN A FROZEN SCUPPER...

22:33.275 --> 22:35.689
DURING THE WINTER MONTHS
IN ALASKA, IN THE BERING SEA,

22:35.689 --> 22:38.344
ICE WILL VERY EASILY
BUILD UP ON SHIPS.

22:38.344 --> 22:40.275
...IS THE ICE ITSELF.

22:40.275 --> 22:42.344
Pruitt: YOU CAN GET
SEVERAL INCHES OF ICE FORMING

22:42.344 --> 22:45.551
ON BOARD A SHIP
OVER SEVERAL MINUTES.

22:45.551 --> 22:47.827
Narrator:
ACCORDING TO NTSB INVESTIGATORS,

22:47.827 --> 22:51.206
AROUND THE TIME
OF THE DESTINATIONSINKING,

22:51.206 --> 22:55.241
2.77 TONS OF ICE WOULD HAVE
ACCUMULATED EVERY 15 MINUTES,

22:55.241 --> 23:01.000
REQUIRING THE CREW TO REMOVE
UP TO 154 EXTRA TONS OF WEIGHT

23:01.000 --> 23:02.896
OVER THE COURSE OF TRANSIT.

23:02.896 --> 23:05.413
♪♪

23:05.413 --> 23:07.103
Phil: WE START TO GET HEAVY,
WE GOT TO START ON

23:07.103 --> 23:09.103
GETTING POTS --
WE GOT TO GET RID OF THEM.

23:09.103 --> 23:11.793
DOESN'T MAKE [BLEEP]
WHERE IT'S AT.

23:11.793 --> 23:13.344
YOU JUST START DUMPING 'EM.

23:13.344 --> 23:15.689
Narrator: IN IDENTICAL
CONDITIONS, CAPTAIN PHIL HARRIS

23:15.689 --> 23:20.137
WAS FORCED TO DUMP HIS GEAR
JUST TO STAY AFLOAT.

23:23.379 --> 23:24.896
Phil: THIS IS A HELL OF A WAY
TO START A SEASON,

23:24.896 --> 23:27.241
THAT'S FOR SURE.

23:27.241 --> 23:30.172
MC HAMMER. HAMMER TIME!

23:31.793 --> 23:34.344
EVEN ON A LARGE
COAST GUARD SHIP,

23:34.344 --> 23:35.689
CREW MEMBERS ARE OUT THERE

23:35.689 --> 23:38.034
WITH BASEBALL BATS AND HAMMERS,
BREAKING ICE,

23:38.034 --> 23:40.551
BECAUSE YOU'RE CONCERNED
ABOUT THE STABILITY OF THE SHIP,

23:40.551 --> 23:41.862
AND YOU'RE CONCERNED
THAT YOUR SHIP

23:41.862 --> 23:43.896
MAY SUCCUMB TO THAT ICE LOAD.

23:46.344 --> 23:48.275
Phil: THE WHOLE THING'S GONNA BE
A PAIN IN THE ASS...

23:48.275 --> 23:50.655
[ SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY ]
REALLY SLOW.

23:50.655 --> 23:54.586
Narrator: ON THE BERING SEA,
DECK ICE FORMS FAST,

23:54.586 --> 23:58.310
BUT CLEARING IT CAN TAKE HOURS.

23:58.310 --> 24:01.862
NOT A GOOD COMBINATION
WHEN CAPSIZING...

24:01.862 --> 24:03.103
Man: [BLEEP] GOLLY!

24:03.103 --> 24:04.862
...CAN HAPPEN IN SECONDS.

24:04.862 --> 24:08.275
YOU HAVE ALL THIS WEIGHT ON TOP,

24:08.275 --> 24:11.206
WHICH IS OVER 100,000 POUNDS,

24:11.206 --> 24:15.103
THEN IT STARTS TILTING,
AND SHE GOES OVER.

24:15.103 --> 24:17.724
AND IT DOESN'T --
IT JUST HAPPENS LIKE THAT.

24:19.620 --> 24:21.000
Phil: WE GOTTA MAKE SURE
WE KEEP AN EYE ON IT.

24:21.000 --> 24:23.689
IT'S WHERE MISTAKES CAN HAPPEN
AND PEOPLE DIE.

24:25.172 --> 24:26.413
IT'S SO COLD, SO QUICK.

24:26.413 --> 24:28.000
ALL YOUR JOINTS MOVE
A LOT SLOWER

24:28.000 --> 24:30.172
AND YOUR MUSCLES
MOVE A LOT SLOWER.

24:30.172 --> 24:31.448
THAT'S COLD.

24:31.448 --> 24:38.448
♪♪

24:38.448 --> 24:41.620
OH, [BLEEP]!

24:41.620 --> 24:43.413
HELL, WITH ALL THIS ICE
AND STUFF,

24:43.413 --> 24:46.000
WHEN I'M TAKING THE CHAINS OFF
ALWAYS MAKES ME NERVOUS.

24:48.413 --> 24:51.517
Narrator: AFTER 40 MINUTES
DANGLING ABOVE THE FRIGID SEA...

24:51.517 --> 24:53.551
Man: WE'RE ALL CLEAR!

24:53.551 --> 24:57.137
...THE CREW FREES THE FIRST POT
FROM THE ICE-HEAVY BOAT.

24:57.137 --> 25:01.655
♪♪

25:01.655 --> 25:04.413
Phil:
THIS IS ONE OF 180 POTS.

25:04.413 --> 25:08.413
IT'S NOT GONNA BE FUN
HERE IN THE FRONT.

25:08.413 --> 25:10.379
Narrator: COULD THIS HAVE BEEN
THE FINAL SCENE

25:10.379 --> 25:12.241
ABOARD THE DESTINATION?

25:12.241 --> 25:15.413
[BLEEP]. IT'LL TAKE FOREVER.

25:15.413 --> 25:17.448
Josh:
SO MUCH ICE ON THIS BOAT.

25:17.448 --> 25:20.551
RIGHT NOW, WE'RE JUST
[BLEEP] FIGHTING FOR SURVIVAL.

25:22.896 --> 25:25.379
WITH THE DESTINATION,YOU KNOW,
YOU'RE TALKING ABOUT A CREW

25:25.379 --> 25:29.172
THAT'S EXPERIENCED AND A CAPTAIN
THAT'S LIVED ON THE OCEAN,

25:29.172 --> 25:32.310
AND FREEZING SPRAY IS,
I BELIEVE, NOT THE ONLY FACTOR.

25:32.310 --> 25:34.172
YOU KNOW, WE ALL DEALT WITH IT.

25:34.172 --> 25:36.896
BUT FOR A BOAT LIKE THAT
TO GO DOWN SO SUDDENLY,

25:36.896 --> 25:40.137
I DON'T THINK FREEZING SPRAY
IS THE ONLY FACTOR HERE.

25:40.137 --> 25:41.344
Narrator: COMING UP...

25:41.344 --> 25:43.344
Jake: THE NUMBER ONE CAUSE
OF BOATS CAPSIZING

25:43.344 --> 25:45.103
IS OVERLOADING THE POTS.

25:45.103 --> 25:46.482
Narrator:
...THE INVESTIGATION NARROWS.

25:46.482 --> 25:49.965
HE WAS ALLOWED TO CARRY
200 POTS AT 700 POUNDS.

25:49.965 --> 25:53.482
THAT'S A LOT OF WEIGHT,
AND NOW THEY'RE INTO THE HEAT

25:53.482 --> 25:55.724
OF WHAT THE BERING SEA HAD
TO THROW AT THEM.

25:55.724 --> 25:58.137
Man: WHOA!

26:00.517 --> 26:03.103
WELL, WE HAVE
A STABILITY TEST GOING ON.

26:03.103 --> 26:06.482
I'VE NEVER SEEN THIS DONE,
SO IT'S PRETTY INTERESTING.

26:06.482 --> 26:09.275
EVERY TIME WE MOVE
THOSE WEIGHTS BACK AND FORTH,

26:09.275 --> 26:10.620
YOU'RE GONNA CHECK THE PENDULUM,

26:10.620 --> 26:13.241
AND YOU CAN SEE
HOW MUCH THE BOAT KEELS

26:13.241 --> 26:16.241
FROM ONE SIDE TO THE OTHER.

26:16.241 --> 26:18.379
Narrator: THE DESTINATIONWAS
THE FIRST CRABBER LOST

26:18.379 --> 26:19.931
IN OVER 12 YEARS.

26:19.931 --> 26:21.931
NOW, TO SAFEGUARD
THE LIVELIHOODS

26:21.931 --> 26:24.965
OF THEIR BOATS AND CREWS,
THE FLEET IS EAGER TO DETERMINE

26:24.965 --> 26:27.344
WHAT FACTORS CONSPIRED
TO CAPSIZE IT

26:27.344 --> 26:30.896
FROM PRECARIOUS SLACK TANKS
TO TOP-HEAVY DECK ICE.

26:30.896 --> 26:34.241
THE CAPTAINS ZERO IN
ON STABILITY.

26:35.896 --> 26:39.931
Sig: IT'S ALL ABOUT THE WEIGHT
OF THE POTS AND HOW HIGH YOU GO.

26:39.931 --> 26:41.413
AND THEN YOU CAN FORMULATE THAT,

26:41.413 --> 26:45.551
WE CAN FIGURE OUT WHAT'S
THE SAFEST LOAD FOR THIS BOAT.

26:45.551 --> 26:46.793
IT'S PRETTY NERVE-RACKING

26:46.793 --> 26:48.724
'CAUSE LAST STABILITY REPORT
WAS AROUND 2000,

26:48.724 --> 26:50.448
I THINK, AND I REALLY FEEL LIKE

26:50.448 --> 26:53.931
I WANT TO HAVE THE SAME AMOUNT
OF POTS, AND SO IT'S SCARY.

26:56.310 --> 26:59.724
Narrator: A CRAB BOAT CAN'T
MAKE MONEY WITHOUT ITS GEAR.

26:59.724 --> 27:01.206
THE MORE POTS YOU CARRY...

27:01.206 --> 27:03.103
THAT'S THE GOOD STUFF.

27:03.103 --> 27:05.137
YEAH!WE'RE GETTING OUR QUOTA.

27:05.137 --> 27:06.827
Narrator: ...THE MORE MONEY
YOU CAN MAKE.

27:06.827 --> 27:10.482
THIS GREAT REWARD ALSO COMES
WITH A GREAT RISK.

27:10.482 --> 27:13.241
THE NUMBER ONE CAUSE OF BOATS
GOING DOWN IS CAPSIZING,

27:13.241 --> 27:16.241
AND THE NUMBER ONE CAUSE
OF BOATS CAPSIZING

27:16.241 --> 27:18.379
IS OVERLOADING THE POTS.

27:20.275 --> 27:21.862
BEAUTIFUL!

27:21.862 --> 27:24.551
Narrator: COULD THE WEIGHT OF
THE DESTINATION'SCRAB POTS

27:24.551 --> 27:27.275
HAVE PLAYED A PART
IN THE BOAT SINKING?

27:27.275 --> 27:30.689
WE DO A STABILITY TEST
SO THAT WE CAN GET AN ESTIMATE

27:30.689 --> 27:33.896
ON HOW MANY POTS WE CAN
CARRY TO THE MAXIMUM,

27:33.896 --> 27:37.275
UNDER WHAT CONDITIONS
WE CAN CARRY THOSE POTS IN,

27:37.275 --> 27:39.103
WHETHER IT'S STORM...

27:39.103 --> 27:41.758
♪♪

27:41.758 --> 27:43.413
Man: IT'S GETTING SCARY.

27:43.413 --> 27:44.586
...ICING...

27:44.586 --> 27:47.310
[ THUD ]HEADS UP.

27:47.310 --> 27:48.965
[ ICE CRACKS ]WATCH OUT.

27:48.965 --> 27:50.758
...AND THE BOTTOM LINE IS,

27:50.758 --> 27:53.448
ANY TIME YOU PUT POTS ON TOP
OF A DECK,

27:53.448 --> 27:56.137
YOU'VE CHANGED THE STABILITY
OF YOUR BOAT, NO MATTER WHAT.

27:56.137 --> 27:57.551
IT'S JUST THE WAY IT IS.

27:57.551 --> 28:02.172
BUT, UH, YOU KNOW, SOMETIMES
OTHER FACTORS COME INTO PLAY

28:02.172 --> 28:06.482
THAT THERE WAS NOTHING
YOU CAN DO ABOUT.

28:06.482 --> 28:09.758
Narrator: JUST THIS SEASON,
CAPTAIN JAKE HAD A CLOSE CALL

28:09.758 --> 28:13.551
WHEN HIS 100,000-POUND STACK
BECAME UNSTABLE.

28:13.551 --> 28:15.344
THESE PASSES
HERE ON THE ALEUTIANS

28:15.344 --> 28:17.724
ARE THE WORST PLACE TO BE
IN HIGH WINDS.

28:20.000 --> 28:23.379
OH, GOD. DON'T HURT ME.
DON'T HURT ME.

28:25.068 --> 28:27.137
THIS IS [BLEEP].

28:29.000 --> 28:30.517
THIS IS A BIG ONE.

28:30.517 --> 28:32.862
OH, [BLEEP]. DON'T HURT US.

28:32.862 --> 28:34.551
DON'T HURT US!

28:34.551 --> 28:36.137
[BLEEP]!

28:39.103 --> 28:41.758
THIS STACK'S STARTING
TO MOVE, SEAN.

28:41.758 --> 28:43.379
IT'S MOVING A LOT.

28:47.241 --> 28:49.482
Narrator: VIOLENT SEAS
LOOSEN THE STACK,

28:49.482 --> 28:54.758
CAUSING 100,000 POUNDS TO SHIFT
RAPIDLY FROM SIDE TO SIDE.

28:54.758 --> 28:58.620
THIS PUTS THE SAGA
IN DANGEROUS RISK OF CAPSIZING.

29:02.379 --> 29:04.068
THE GUYS JUST GETTING OUT THERE

29:04.068 --> 29:07.965
TO TIGHTEN THE CHAINS UP
IN 25, 30-FOOT SEAS.

29:10.551 --> 29:11.896
WHOA!

29:11.896 --> 29:15.586
DRYDEN, CHECK THAT
ONE OVER THERE.

29:15.586 --> 29:17.172
COME ON, YOU GUYS.

29:20.344 --> 29:22.413
COME ON.

29:22.413 --> 29:24.344
COME ON!

29:24.344 --> 29:28.931
THE WEATHER IS JUST GETTING
WORSE AND WORSE BY THE MINUTE.

29:28.931 --> 29:30.275
Man: GONZO!

29:30.275 --> 29:34.551
I DON'T SEE IT SHIFT ANYMORE.
THAT'S GOOD.

29:34.551 --> 29:36.413
ALRIGHT, JAKE. STACK SECURE.

29:39.344 --> 29:40.931
MAN.

29:40.931 --> 29:43.655
I WAS -- I WAS SCARED
[BLEEP]LESS.

29:43.655 --> 29:46.206
EVEN THOUGH CAPTAIN JAKE
FOLLOWED THE STABILITY REPORT

29:46.206 --> 29:49.896
PROTOCOL FOR CARRYING POTS
IN STORMY WEATHER...

29:49.896 --> 29:51.896
JUST GLAD NOBODY GOT HURT.

29:51.896 --> 29:56.482
...THE SAGA STILL CAME
VERY CLOSE TO A TRAGIC OUTCOME.

29:56.482 --> 29:58.896
WAS THIS CLOSE CALL AN INSIGHT

29:58.896 --> 30:01.827
AS TO WHAT COULD HAVE HAPPENED
TO THE DESTINATION?

30:01.827 --> 30:04.000
I THINK AFTER DESTINATIONSANK,

30:04.000 --> 30:06.862
THE GUYS STARTED TAKING A LOOK
AT THEIR STABILITY

30:06.862 --> 30:09.793
AND WHAT THEIR BOATS
CAN DO AND CAN'T DO.

30:09.793 --> 30:12.206
IT DOESN'T HURT TO UPDATE IT
ONCE IN A WHILE.

30:12.206 --> 30:14.172
BOATS ADD MORE STEEL
OVER THE YEARS.

30:14.172 --> 30:16.344
THEY ADD DIFFERENT POTS
OVER THE YEARS.

30:16.344 --> 30:18.103
Sean: THE STABILITY REPORT
FOR THE DESTINATION

30:18.103 --> 30:19.827
WAS ALMOST 30 YEARS OLD.

30:19.827 --> 30:21.689
NO ONE HAS 30-YEAR-OLD POTS.

30:21.689 --> 30:23.655
IT JUST DOESN'T EXIST.
THEY WEAR OUT.

30:23.655 --> 30:25.103
THEY'RE A CONSUMABLE.

30:25.103 --> 30:27.620
♪♪

30:27.620 --> 30:29.862
-Man: WHOA!
-Sean: POTS ARE CONSUMED

30:29.862 --> 30:33.620
BY THE BERING SEA
AND HOW WE FISH.

30:33.620 --> 30:36.206
Narrator: OVER THE YEARS,
MANUFACTURERS HAVE ADDED

30:36.206 --> 30:38.965
MORE STEEL TO POTS IN AN EFFORT
TO STRENGTHEN THEM

30:38.965 --> 30:41.103
AGAINST THE RIGORS
OF CRAB FISHING.

30:41.103 --> 30:43.206
[ THUD ]AND YOU REPLACE 20 ONE YEAR

30:43.206 --> 30:45.793
AND 10 THE NEXT YEAR
AND 40 THE NEXT YEAR.

30:45.793 --> 30:46.862
YOU KNOW, AND ALL OF A SUDDEN,

30:46.862 --> 30:48.379
YOU GOT
A BRAND-NEW STACK OF GEAR

30:48.379 --> 30:51.586
THAT'S NOTHING LIKE THE STACK
YOU HAD EVEN FIVE YEARS AGO.

30:51.586 --> 30:55.172
I'M CONSTANTLY BUYING NEW GEAR.

30:55.172 --> 30:57.000
YOU'RE PUTTING THAT ON.
YOU DON'T KNOW WHAT IT WEIGHS.

30:57.000 --> 31:02.034
YOU THINK IT'S 6.5x6.5-FOOT POT.
IT SHOULD WEIGH 650 POUNDS.

31:02.034 --> 31:03.827
THAT WAS ALWAYS THE RATE.

31:03.827 --> 31:07.103
MINE WEIGH 789 POUNDS,

31:07.103 --> 31:09.103
SO I WAS WAYOVER.

31:09.103 --> 31:12.448
SO, FOR THE FIRST TWO YEARS
OF MY CAREER AS A CAPTAIN,

31:12.448 --> 31:16.206
I THOUGHT I WAS 20 POTS UNDER
STABILITY REPORT.

31:16.206 --> 31:20.137
I WAS ACTUALLY
DAMN NEAR 40 POTS OVER

31:20.137 --> 31:23.655
WHAT I WAS ALLOWED TO CARRY,
'CAUSE IDIDN'T CHECK.

31:23.655 --> 31:25.724
Narrator: COULD THE DESTINATION
HAVE UNWITTINGLY BEEN

31:25.724 --> 31:28.931
CARRYING HEAVIER POTS THAN
SHE WAS RATED FOR?

31:28.931 --> 31:32.103
THE NTSB REPORT THAT
THE COAST GUARD HELPED WITH

31:32.103 --> 31:33.965
AND THE CALCULATIONS THAT WERE
THERE FOR THE DESTINATION

31:33.965 --> 31:37.034
WAS THAT SHE WAS ALLOWED
TO CARRY 200 POTS

31:37.034 --> 31:39.103
AT 700 POUNDS A PIECE.

31:39.103 --> 31:40.517
THE REALITY WAS THAT THE POTS

31:40.517 --> 31:42.551
THAT THEY ACTUALLY RECOVERED
FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE OCEAN

31:42.551 --> 31:46.448
NEXT TO THE DESTINATIONWAS
A POT THAT WEIGHED 840 POUNDS.

31:46.448 --> 31:48.655
140 POUNDS TIMES 200 --

31:48.655 --> 31:51.241
SHE WAS CARRYING 14 TONS
OF TOPSIDE WEIGHT

31:51.241 --> 31:52.517
THAT YOU COULD ESSENTIALLY SAY

31:52.517 --> 31:55.000
WAS ADDED TO THIS VESSEL
THAT WASN'T PLANNED FOR.

31:55.000 --> 31:58.241
THAT'S A LOT OF WEIGHT
TO PUT HIGH UP ON A VESSEL

31:58.241 --> 32:01.034
THAT'S SUPPOSED TO BE TRYING
TO STAY AS STABLE AS POSSIBLE.

32:01.034 --> 32:05.448
ADD THAT TO ICING,
WIND, AND WAVES,

32:05.448 --> 32:08.793
AND YOU'VE GOT A DISASTER
IN THE MAKING.

32:08.793 --> 32:10.655
Narrator:
THE NIGHT THE DESTINATIONSANK,

32:10.655 --> 32:14.206
THE NATIONAL WEATHER SERVICE
CALLED FOR HEAVY FREEZING SPRAY,

32:14.206 --> 32:17.586
30-KNOT WINDS,
AND 10-FOOT SEAS,

32:17.586 --> 32:20.241
AN OMINOUS TRIFECTA
WAITING FOR THE BOAT

32:20.241 --> 32:23.655
AS IT CLEARED
THE LEE OF ST. GEORGE ISLAND.

32:23.655 --> 32:26.137
Pruitt: SO AS DESTINATIONCAME
AROUND ST. GEORGE ISLAND,

32:26.137 --> 32:28.551
THEY WOULD HAVE BEEN EXPOSED
TO ALL THE FORCES

32:28.551 --> 32:30.482
THAT MOTHER NATURE HAD IN STORE.

32:30.482 --> 32:33.379
THEY WOULD HAVE BROKEN THAT LEE,
THAT PROTECTIVE BARRIER,

32:33.379 --> 32:37.172
AND NOW THEY'RE INTO,
ESSENTIALLY, THE HEAT

32:37.172 --> 32:39.379
OF WHAT THE BERING SEA HAD
TO THROW AT THEM.

32:39.379 --> 32:43.413
SO THEY COULD HAVE BEEN EXPOSED
TO HIGH WINDS, HIGH SEAS,

32:43.413 --> 32:45.379
AND EVEN POTENTIALLY
A ROGUE WAVE.

32:45.379 --> 32:52.655
♪♪

32:52.655 --> 32:56.000
THIS IS UNBELIEVABLE.

32:56.000 --> 32:58.931
Narrator: CAPTAIN JERRY TILLEY
JOGS THE ALEUTIAN BALLAD

32:58.931 --> 33:01.655
THROUGH 40-FOOT MIXED SEAS.

33:01.655 --> 33:04.482
♪♪

33:04.482 --> 33:05.655
Jerry: NO!

33:05.655 --> 33:07.517
[ GLASS SHATTERS ]

33:07.517 --> 33:09.068
[ MAN SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY ]

33:13.655 --> 33:16.965
Narrator: A ROGUE WAVE,
WEIGHING IN AT OVER 100 TONS,

33:16.965 --> 33:20.241
BLINDSIDES THE VESSEL.

33:20.241 --> 33:24.103
A ROGUE WAVE IS ESSENTIALLY
AN OUT-OF-SYNC WAVE.

33:24.103 --> 33:27.275
SO IF WAVES ARE GOING
IN ONE DIRECTION AS A TREND,

33:27.275 --> 33:30.620
A ROGUE WAVE IS ANOTHER WAVE
THAT COMES OUT OF NOWHERE

33:30.620 --> 33:33.275
OUT OF A COMPLETELY DIFFERENT
DIRECTION.

33:33.275 --> 33:36.620
Narrator: THIS 100-FOOT MONSTER
WAS ONE OF THE FIRST ROGUE WAVES

33:36.620 --> 33:38.827
EVER TO BE CAUGHT ON CAMERA.

33:38.827 --> 33:41.103
♪♪

33:44.241 --> 33:45.655
Man: CHIEF?

33:47.482 --> 33:49.758
Man: GOT NO STEERING.

33:49.758 --> 33:52.862
Narrator: THE COLLISION RIPS
A 20-FOOT HOLE OUT OF THE DECK

33:52.862 --> 33:56.586
AND SHUTS DOWN POWER
TO THE WHEELHOUSE.

33:56.586 --> 33:58.620
FORTUNATELY
FOR THE ALEUTIAN BALLAD,

33:58.620 --> 34:03.344
THEY WERE ABLE TO RESTORE POWER
AND LIMP BACK TO PORT.

34:03.344 --> 34:05.172
I MEAN, LOOK AT
THE ALEUTIAN BALLAD

34:05.172 --> 34:06.379
WHEN THAT THING GOT HIT.

34:06.379 --> 34:08.000
THEY DIDN'T HAVE ANY GEAR
ON DECK,

34:08.000 --> 34:10.379
AND HAD YOU HAD A BUNCH
OF GEAR ON BOARD,

34:10.379 --> 34:13.241
I THINK THEY'D HAVE BEEN
IN BIG TROUBLE.

34:13.241 --> 34:16.344
BASED ON THE ESTIMATION
OF HOW MUCH WEIGHT

34:16.344 --> 34:18.310
WAS ON BOARD THE DESTINATION
AT THE TIME

34:18.310 --> 34:21.275
AND POTENTIALLY OVERLOADING,
INCLUDING ICE,

34:21.275 --> 34:23.103
IT PROBABLY WOULDN'T HAVE TAKEN
EVEN A ROGUE WAVE

34:23.103 --> 34:24.516
TO JUST KNOCK IT OVER.

34:24.516 --> 34:28.000
GETTING HIT FROM THE BEAM
BY HIGH WIND,

34:28.000 --> 34:30.862
AND EVEN JUST A NORMAL SEA
STATE, COULD HAVE BEEN ENOUGH.

34:30.862 --> 34:33.965
♪♪

34:33.965 --> 34:35.516
Narrator: COMING UP...

34:35.516 --> 34:37.757
THE MORAL OF THE STORY IS THAT
THE SINKING OF THE DESTINATION

34:37.757 --> 34:39.931
WILL SAVE OTHER LIVES.

34:39.931 --> 34:43.551
...THE NTSB FINDINGS
ARE REVEALED...

34:43.551 --> 34:46.585
IT CHANGED FISHING FOR EVERYBODY
THAT'S DRIVING A BOAT.

34:46.585 --> 34:48.310
I WANT TO BE AS SAFE
AS WE POSSIBLY CAN.

34:48.310 --> 34:49.516
WE ALWAYS WANT TO COME HOME.

34:49.516 --> 34:52.447
...AND THE FLEET IS CHANGED
FOREVER.

34:54.275 --> 34:55.688
Narrator:
THIS WEEK ON "SALTY TAKES",

34:55.688 --> 34:59.068
DESTINATIONCAPTAIN
JEFF HATHAWAY SAVES THE DAY.

34:59.068 --> 35:01.137
Sig: I REMEMBER A TIME
WHERE NORTHWESTERN

35:01.137 --> 35:03.482
WAS FISHING COD OUT IN ADEK.

35:03.482 --> 35:07.310
WE MANAGED TO HIT
THE ONLY SANDY SPOT

35:07.310 --> 35:10.206
ON THESE ROCKY CLIFFS.

35:10.206 --> 35:12.310
THE BOAT WAS SIDEWAYS.

35:12.310 --> 35:13.827
WAVES WERE CRASHING
INTO THE BOAT,

35:13.827 --> 35:16.379
AND I WAS IN COMPLETE PANIC.

35:16.379 --> 35:18.482
I THOUGHT THAT WAS IT.

35:18.482 --> 35:21.551
GUYS WERE IN THEIR SUITS.
WE WERE READY TO BAIL.

35:21.551 --> 35:24.241
THE GUY THAT I WENT TO FIRST
WAS JEFF.

35:24.241 --> 35:28.896
JEFF WAS A WAY BETTER FISHERMAN
THAN SIG, AND SIG KNEW THAT.

35:28.896 --> 35:30.551
Sig:
HE MANAGED TO CALM ME DOWN,

35:30.551 --> 35:32.103
AND HE KIND OF MADE A JOKE
OUT OF IT.

35:32.103 --> 35:33.379
BUT HE WAS LIKE, "COME ON!

35:33.379 --> 35:35.724
"YOU'RE NOT THE FIRST GUY
TO HIT THE BEACH.

35:35.724 --> 35:37.137
IT'S FINE."

35:37.137 --> 35:40.241
AND I'M SCREAMING. HE GOES,
"WOULD YOU JUST CALM DOWN?

35:40.241 --> 35:42.103
"YOU KNOW, IT HAPPENS
ALL THE TIME.

35:42.103 --> 35:43.551
WE'LL GET YA."

35:43.551 --> 35:44.724
I CAME TO.

35:44.724 --> 35:46.689
IT WAS LIKE
I JUST SNAPPED OUT OF IT.

35:46.689 --> 35:50.344
I KIND OF LIKE JEFF'S VERSION
BETTER 'CAUSE SIG LEAVES OUT

35:50.344 --> 35:51.965
ALL THE PARTS OF THE STORY
THAT MAKE HIM LOOK BAD.

35:51.965 --> 35:53.793
SIG WAS SO WORRIED ABOUT
BREAKING THE LINE

35:53.793 --> 35:55.551
THAT HE DIDN'T WANT TO GET
A BIG JERK ON IT,

35:55.551 --> 35:57.724
AND JEFF WAS LIKE,
"ONE-SHOT WONDER.

35:57.724 --> 35:59.689
HERE WE GO", AND LAID ON IT.

35:59.689 --> 36:03.379
SO WE GOT HER IN REVERSE
AND THEN WAS ABLE TO PULL THAT

36:03.379 --> 36:05.310
200 TONS OF STEEL
OFF THE BEACH.

36:05.310 --> 36:06.655
JEFF SAVED SIG'S ONIONS,

36:06.655 --> 36:08.724
'CAUSE IF THE TIDE WOULD HAVE
GONE OUT,

36:08.724 --> 36:10.310
I'M SURE HE WOULD HAVE GOT
HIS ASS KICKED ON THE BEACH.

36:10.310 --> 36:11.965
HAD IT NOT BEEN FOR JEFF,

36:11.965 --> 36:13.793
I WOULD HAVE ABANDONED SHIP
RIGHT THERE.

36:13.793 --> 36:15.862
♪♪

36:17.241 --> 36:19.137
♪♪

36:19.137 --> 36:22.758
Sig: THE BIG QUESTION IS
WHY THERE WAS NO MAYDAY CALL.

36:22.758 --> 36:24.586
Casey: I THINK WHOEVER
WAS ON THE WHEEL

36:24.586 --> 36:26.965
WAS NOT IN THE WHEELHOUSE.

36:26.965 --> 36:28.275
Prout: HOW DID THAT GET
TAPED TOGETHER?

36:28.275 --> 36:30.758
THAT WAS DONE BY SOMEBODY.

36:30.758 --> 36:33.551
Narrator: WITH THE DESTINATION
RESTING ON THE OCEAN FLOOR,

36:33.551 --> 36:37.413
ANSWERS TO THE MYSTERY
CAN NEVER BE DEFINITIVE.

36:37.413 --> 36:39.896
BUT THE NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION
SAFETY BOARD

36:39.896 --> 36:43.206
CONCLUDED THAT HEAVIER POTS
AND ICE ACCUMULATION

36:43.206 --> 36:47.068
WERE THE PROBABLE CAUSE THAT
COMPROMISED THE BOAT'S STABILITY

36:47.068 --> 36:49.413
AND LED TO HER CAPSIZING.

36:49.413 --> 36:52.068
THESE REVELATIONS HAVE FORCED
EVERY CAPTAIN

36:52.068 --> 36:54.827
TO REEXAMINE
THEIR OWN BOATS' STABILITY

36:54.827 --> 36:58.586
AND THE PRECISE WEIGHT
OF THEIR POTS.

36:58.586 --> 36:59.931
Sean: THE MORAL OF THE STORY

36:59.931 --> 37:01.310
IS THAT THE SINKING
OF THE DESTINATION

37:01.310 --> 37:05.000
WILL SAVE OTHER LIVES,
AND IT WILL TEACH US

37:05.000 --> 37:07.241
TO LEARN FROM OUR PAST MISTAKES.

37:07.241 --> 37:10.103
AND I'M REALLY SAD THAT IT CAME
AT THE EXPENSE

37:10.103 --> 37:12.620
OF SOME REALLY PROFESSIONAL
OPERATORS.

37:12.620 --> 37:18.206
♪♪

37:18.206 --> 37:19.655
Keith over radio:
Security, security, security,

37:19.655 --> 37:21.827
Wizardoutbound captain
speaking,

37:21.827 --> 37:23.793
transmitting east side.

37:25.724 --> 37:28.586
Sig over radio:
Right now, I'm doing 20 degrees.

37:28.586 --> 37:30.000
WE'LL JUST GET INTO A CIRCLE,

37:30.000 --> 37:34.172
AND, UH,
WE'LL TAKE OUR TIME HERE.

37:34.172 --> 37:36.448
Keith:
WE NEED GUYS UP IN THE MAST.

37:36.448 --> 37:39.482
♪♪

37:39.482 --> 37:41.310
STAND BY. STAND BY.

37:44.241 --> 37:46.517
Narrator:
JUST OUTSIDE DUTCH HARBOR...

37:46.517 --> 37:47.862
Sig over radio:
I don't want to play preacher.

37:47.862 --> 37:52.448
I just want to give tribute
to our friends.

37:52.448 --> 37:55.379
...BEFORE THE START OF
THE FOLLOWING KING CRAB SEASON,

37:55.379 --> 37:57.655
THE FLEET HONORS THE SIX MEN

37:57.655 --> 38:01.103
WHO TRAGICALLY LOST THEIR LIVES
ON THE BERING SEA.

38:03.517 --> 38:05.586
I CAN'T BELIEVE THEY'RE GONE.

38:07.241 --> 38:09.517
IT'S BEEN A COUPLE OF YEARS NOW
SINCE THE DESTINATIONWENT DOWN,

38:09.517 --> 38:12.620
AND IT WAS A SHOT
ACROSS THE BOW.

38:12.620 --> 38:16.689
EVERYBODY'S CHANGED IN ONE WAY
OR ANOTHER, I BELIEVE.

38:16.689 --> 38:19.000
Bill: IT CHANGED
THE OUTLOOK OF FISHING.

38:19.000 --> 38:21.586
IF IT DIDN'T DO IT FOR EVERYBODY
THAT'S DRIVING A BOAT,

38:21.586 --> 38:24.275
IT SHOULD HAVE.
-IT REALLY MAKES YOU THINK,

38:24.275 --> 38:27.206
"THIS COULD HAPPEN TO ME
ANY DAY."

38:27.206 --> 38:29.413
MAYBE I NEED TO
DOUBLE OR TRIPLE-CHECK

38:29.413 --> 38:30.758
EVERY TANK ALARM.

38:30.758 --> 38:33.103
MAYBE I NEED TO GO
AND RECOUNT MY POTS,

38:33.103 --> 38:35.517
ALL THIS STUFF.

38:35.517 --> 38:37.103
Bill: I'VE PULLED BACK
ON PUSHING THE LIMIT

38:37.103 --> 38:40.103
ON WHAT I PUT ON MY BOAT
FOR POTS AND BAIT.

38:40.103 --> 38:44.551
EVERYBODY IS LOOKING AT RENEWING
THEIR STABILITY LETTERS.

38:44.551 --> 38:47.724
OUR STABILITY TEST IS ONE OF
THE NEWEST ONES OUT THERE.

38:47.724 --> 38:50.172
WE WENT AND REDID IT
BECAUSE OF THE DESTINATION.

38:50.172 --> 38:52.586
WE HAVE UPDATED
OUR STABILITY REPORT.

38:52.586 --> 38:56.068
RIGHT NOW, MINE'S FROM '95,
AND THAT'S GOING TO CHANGE.

38:56.068 --> 38:58.310
COAST GUARD'S NOW WEIGHING POTS.

38:58.310 --> 39:02.172
CREW MEMBERS ARE THINKING TWICE
BEFORE PASSING OFF

39:02.172 --> 39:04.137
THAT WHEEL WATCH
TO THE NEXT GUIDE.

39:04.137 --> 39:05.862
WE WANNA BE AS SAFE AS
WE POSSIBLY CAN.

39:05.862 --> 39:07.310
WE ALWAYS WANT TO COME HOME.

39:07.310 --> 39:11.034
♪♪

39:11.034 --> 39:15.344
Sig: FOR ME PERSONALLY,
I'M MUCH MORE CAUTIOUS.

39:15.344 --> 39:18.103
YOU KNOW, MY STABILITY REPORT
JUST CAME IN.

39:18.103 --> 39:23.689
I WENT FROM 170 POTS MAXIMUM
TO 165 POTS MAXIMUM,

39:23.689 --> 39:25.862
AND, UH, THAT'S A NUMBER
I CAN LIVE WITH.

39:25.862 --> 39:27.413
THAT'S A SMALL PRICE TO PAY
FOR ME.

39:27.413 --> 39:33.310
AT LEAST I KNOW THAT MY CREW,
MY FAMILY, MY BOAT IS SAFE.

39:34.689 --> 39:35.862
READY?

39:35.862 --> 39:38.413
ONE, TWO, THREE.

39:38.413 --> 39:42.137
♪♪

39:42.137 --> 39:44.103
Bill: WHEN YOU DO
AN ORGANIZED MEMORIAL,

39:44.103 --> 39:45.655
IT'S WITH YOU ALL THE TIME.

39:45.655 --> 39:49.241
YOU'RE ALWAYS THINKING LITTLE
FLASHES OF THROWING HORSESHOES

39:49.241 --> 39:51.241
OR PLAYING SOFTBALL
AT SAND POINT.

39:51.241 --> 39:53.068
LITTLE FLASHES OF THE BOAT

39:53.068 --> 39:55.000
GOING OUT
AT 5:00 IN THE MORNING.

39:55.000 --> 39:58.000
I MEAN, YOU JUST HAVE
ALL THE MEMORIES OF THE GOOD,

39:58.000 --> 40:02.103
AND A MEMORIAL...

40:02.103 --> 40:04.172
TELLS YOU THAT THAT'S OVER.

40:04.172 --> 40:05.758
Josh: GOD BLESS THEM.

40:05.758 --> 40:08.586
♪♪

40:08.586 --> 40:10.620
Sig: EVERY TIME I THINK
OF SAFETY,

40:10.620 --> 40:13.586
I THINK OF JEFF AND THE BOAT.

40:13.586 --> 40:18.103
IF I COULD TALK TO JEFF, I WOULD
THANK HIM FOR BEING A MENTOR.

40:18.103 --> 40:20.827
[ Voice breaks ] AND I THINK
HE DIDN'T DIE IN VAIN.

40:23.448 --> 40:26.000
SO...

40:26.000 --> 40:28.689
YEAH. THEY DIDN'T DIE IN VAIN.

40:28.689 --> 40:33.793
♪♪

40:33.793 --> 40:38.931
♪♪

40:38.931 --> 40:41.517
Sig over radio: It's times like
this that reminds us

40:41.517 --> 40:45.689
exactly how fragile
our lives are.

40:45.689 --> 40:49.517
Times like this
make you dig deep.

40:49.517 --> 40:51.758
We don't have time to stop.

40:51.758 --> 40:54.137
We're here to go catch crab.

40:54.137 --> 40:56.965
That's just the bottom line.

40:56.965 --> 41:00.241
Let's go fishing and remember
those who we lost,

41:00.241 --> 41:01.965
BUT MOVE FORWARD OURSELVES.

41:01.965 --> 41:03.827
AGREED?

41:03.827 --> 41:06.034
-Man over radio: Agreed.
-AGREED.

41:06.034 --> 41:07.379
Sig over radio:
Okay, guys.

41:07.379 --> 41:10.379
Three, two, one...light 'em up.

41:10.379 --> 41:13.034
Man over radio: Strike
your flares. Strike your flares.

41:13.034 --> 41:20.103
♪♪

